author: lightclient
content:
Nice to see many of you in Amsterdam! If you're wondering what the status of the builder api + mev-boost is please see the following:
* preparing to merge builder api spec into execution apis - this will be cut into a release soon after for CLs to target: https://github.com/ethereum/execution-apis/pull/209
* beacon-api modification to allow the validator to sign a `registerValidator` msg (previously `setFeeRecipient`): https://github.com/ethereum/beacon-APIs/pull/206
* consensus-spec update to allow validators to sign application-specific messages, rather than only in-protocol messages: https://github.com/ethereum/consensus-specs/pull/2882
* many short/medium term research questions opened in the mev-boost repository: https://github.com/flashbots/mev-boost/issues

author: lightclient
content: There is also an immediate question from <@539495253418180618> about whether the validator should control the gas limit or the builder should. I'm inclined to say that the validator's "target gas limit" should be included in the `RegisterValidator` message. This seems to map nicely to how clients currently allow miners to signal their gas limit preference (via cli flags usually) and builders can then calculate i) the largest possible move towards their desired limit or ii) immediately construct a block with the preferred target gas limit.

author: m.kalinin
content: What is the rationale behind using validator's `pubkey` instead of `index`?

author: metachris_
content: Only convenience, not necessity. It saves the builders a lookup. At the workshop  on mev-day the opinion was to simply add it because it's free.

author: m.kalinin
content: The problem is that builder will have to check if a `pubkey` belongs to existing validators, otherwise, builder may be DoSed and registry may be overflown by fee recipient addresses of non-existing validators. So, the lookup seems necessary

author: m.kalinin
content: Also, in a direct communication scenario do we need a builder to provide its `pubkey` and sign a message? Or is this now in data structures to provide future compatibility?

author: metachris_
content: Hmm good point, builders will need to look it up. In this case adding the pubkey doesn't offer additional benefits, and just using `validator_index` + `timestamp` + `fee_recipient` should be fine. (~~I couldn't immediately find the beacon-API to get the `pubkey` for a given `validator_index` though~~ probably https://ethereum.github.io/beacon-APIs/#/ValidatorRequiredApi/getStateValidator)

author: lightclient
content: One idea behind using pubkey is that it bundles everything necessary to cryptographically verify the message together (idx requires an additional lookup). I think the benefit turns out to be marginal at best though because keys can be generated on demand to sign spam.

author: tbenr
content: yes, the path is: `eth/v1/beacon/states/head/validators/<index>`

author: metachris_
content:
Thinking on it some more, builders would also need some more information before the block building process starts (before `getHeader` is called):
- `timestamp` (value for the timestamp field of the new payload)
- `prevRandao` (value for the prevRandao field of the new payload)

And perhaps (could be part of `builder_registerValidator`):
- `extraData` (unless it comes from the builder)
- maybe: preferred/required gas limit target

Maybe all of these should just be set by the builder, not the proposer (which would a straight-forward solution without a lot of additional update calls to mev-boost)  ðŸ¤” (cc/ <@539495253418180618>)

author: lightclient
content: <@388610194608750595> the builders won't need  `prevrandao` because it can be determined from the previous slot

author: lightclient
content:
- `extraData` : I don't feel strongly one way or another about, it might be simplest to just assume the `GetHeader` will also have it as an input and the builder _must_ recompute the execution payload hash
- `gasLimit` : this seems like it should be done during the validator registration. It won't change much and avoids give the builders total control over the limit

author: m.kalinin
content: how will proposer validate the `gasLimit` is set according to its preferences?

author: metachris_
content: It's part of the `ExecutionPayloadHeader`, and the relay could verify that before sending the header to the validator.

author: metachris_
content:
> - extraData : I don't feel strongly one way or another about, it might be simplest to just assume the GetHeader will also have it as an input and the builder must recompute the execution payload hash
We could only do that if `getHeader` is authenticated (signed), otherwise it opens up to spam/ddos attacks. Should this even come from the proposer? Maybe it should actually come from the builder anyway. Would also be the easiest solution (otherwise i'd see that in `builder_registerValidator`).

author: metachris_
content: Dropping the updated system diagram here so everyone has the full context (builders submitting header + payload together to the relay, which acts as escrow and verifies the value, feeRecipient and all other necessary properties):

author: m.kalinin
content: `gasLimit` can't be set to arbitrary value, it has a limitation on the difference wrt parent block value. Proposer may check if `gasLimit` is adjusted according to its preferences, it would need some logic on CL side

author: metachris_
content: I guess the relay could verify it, in addition to checking that the payload actually has the value and pays to feeRecipient (it is trusted in that way already).

author: ralexstokes
content:
the even lower-res thing to do *now* is to simply let validators commit to a target in `builder_registerValidator`

some (offline, even) process can check after the fact and raise a loud off-chain alarm (e.g. twitter) if foul play is detected

author: ralexstokes
content: i think it is **critical** that validators retain control of the gas limit and that this power is not given to builders
